            "author_info": {
                "name": "Armands Skutelis",
                "href": "/profile/Armands-Skutelis"
            },
            "answer_text": "Some probably want it. But then they do not consider the Baltic state they live in as ''their'' country. Probably even modern Russia is not really their country, only some imagined wonderful version of it, like new kind of USSR. They want to join a dream, a childhood memory, and a brand called ''Putin has turned Russia into superpower again'' which means very little in real life when bills are to be paid. Yes, probably part of the reason is to see Russian writing in big letters all around them and their culture as dominant, same way as we do not want to see that and find Russian cyrillic writing at best ''weird'' (and at our worst... well you can imagine what ultra ''patriotic'' people would say) and decidedly non-European (in our interpretation of what Europe is). ",
